 public enemies when\neddMNding automobiles and should be \u201cper\nsusded\u2019* to let others drive in peace. Just\nI harause alee people\u201d sometimes commit\nihi* offense is no reason to encourage the\nHabit It is s crime and should be prompt\nimniabed as a crime. To do this will\nves in 1949.\nWHAT AROUT COLLECE?\nre beginning to close and a\n1,1 y Unf P oP,e wIU into the\nmaking money. Too many\nI*\"** th#ir \"cholastic training at the\nend of high school days without realia\ntMf ills tremendous advantages that will\nl romu to them by pursuing their way\nthrough college.\nThe Citizen does not recommend a col.\ni ounce for every boy or girl. There was\n11 Um w,len lop!e thought this was a\n.good idea, but undoubtedly, there are\nl,o y* n W Who will not take ad.\nof the educational opportunities\nthat can be obtained. These might as well\n15 <%4 i'l rork> whth r they are the sons and\ndaughters of rich or poor parents.\n\u2666At tha same time, let us urge all stu\n.dtiiu who will complete their high\nJ courK<?l summer, to give seri\nOU* thought to the possibility of attend.\n\u2022au college. The right institution, and the\na***** s\nCONTINUE TO FALL\nAnybody who reads magazines de\nvoted to business in its broadest sense, or\narticles about business in magazines and\nnewspapers, can readily determine that we\nare in the throes of recession. One fipiaga\n%zine, with a circulation of more than 2.500,-\n000. devoted all except one of its business\narticles last week to*the recession.*\nThe recession is underpray in Key\nWest as well as in all other cities in Flori\nda. Tampa and Miami report that even\nittriita buying is tapering off.\nThe magazine assigns the reason for\nthe recession to a determined stand by the\npublic to resist buying during skyrocket\ning prices in many fields. One article list\ned several 'corporations that do business\non a nationwide scale that recently have\nannounced cuts in prices ranging up to 20\npercent. But buying responses are still\nslow and cautious. The public feels that\nfar greater reductions most be made be\nfore it opens up Its pocketbook for pur\nchasing on a large scale.\nIt was explained in the articles that\nthe American people still hare vast\namounts of savings. Continuation of un\nemployment seems to have been viewed by\nthe people as a warning to buy carefully\nand to sidestep high prices whenever pos\nsible.\nTaxicab drivers in Key West proba\nbly are the first group to note an increase\nor falling off of business. When no dose\ncheck is made on \u201cspending\u201d monejCtyte\ndrivers do a thriving business, but they\nhave reported for several weeks that\n\u201cfares\u201d have been declining. That trend\nhas been evident in some other lines of\nbusiness in Key West.\nHowever, residents have no cause yet\nfor uneasiness. More Key Westers than\nhad been expected put away that \u201cnest\negg.\" when business was good, for the\nproverbial rainy day. It is true that unem\nployment exists her, but it is probably on\na lower scale, viewed from a standpoint of\npopulation, than elsewhere in Florida.\nFinally, as long as buyer resistence\ncontinues, prices will continue to fall.\nRubbing against a tough proposition\nwill either polish a man up or finish him\noff.\nHard work and no play is bad, but not\nnearly as bad as no work and too much\nplay.\nA racket is somebody else\u2019* formula\nfor making a living without too much\nwork.\nA HELPLESS MINORITY\nThe United Nations now includes\nfifty-nine members, involving a hetero\ngeneous collection of small and large,\nbackward and progressive, strong and de\nfenseless and, we might add, civilized and\nnear-civilized countries.\nThe United States, Great Britain,\nFrance and Russia, sometimes' referred to\nas the Big Four, constitute the backbone\nof the strength of the organization. When\nacting in concert, they have the resources,\npower and ability. However, they have\nonly four votes out of fifty-nine. This, in\nlarge degree, explains their possession\nof the veto prerogative.\nThis misuse of the veto by Soviet Rus\nsia should not blind us to the obvious\nadvantages of such an arrangement. Only\nthrough concerted action of the larger\nnations <?an the United Nations function\nas it was intended to operate. It is better\nfor the organiation not to undertake a\nquestionable task rather than to plunge\ninto it with the larger nations divided and\nantagonistic.\nThere is another phase of the opera\ntions of the United Nations which should\nreceive the attention of the people of this\ncountry. Most of the members, regardless\nof all the talk about the four freedoms,\ndo not seriously apply them at home.\nMoreover, what is generally referred to\nas the Anglo-Saxon civilization is shared\nby not more than ten of twelve of the\nmembers. In addition, the membership is\nbroken up Into a number of groups acting\nthrough something of a mutual self-in\nterest. This would include a Latin bloc,\na Near East bloc, an Asiatic bloc, a Com\nmunist bloc and some other delineations.\nSo long as the United Nations con\nfines itself to the general peace of the\nworld, which is obviously in the interest\nof all the nations, and seeks to prevent\naggressive attacks upon free nations, it can\nhope to move, in the future, with soli\ndarity. Whenever it dips into the domes\ntic business of the various states, regard\nless of motives, it treads on dangerous\ngrounds.\nTHE KEY WEST CITIZEN\nMISSED THE BOAT AGAIN By MACKENZIE\ni-*,\nV\n\n*4NXI\u00a3\nKey Vest in*\nDays Gone By\nAt TAKEN PROM PILES\nOF TNK CITIZEN OF\nMAY BA IMS\nAll government forces joined\nwith local veterans in observing\nMemorial Day today at the Maine\nplot in City Cemetery.\nAlbert G.. Roberts, who is con\nnected with the U. S. Public\nHealth Service in Washington,\nwrites The Citizen that he and\nfour friends will leave on June\n5 for a visit to Atlantic City and\nthen for Key West.\nThe two-masted schooner A. M.\nAdams arrived yesterday from\noff the coast of Nicaragua with\na cargo of 300 turtle.\nThe senate today passed a bill,\nsponsored by David Elmer Ward,\nthat provides for the payment of\n$674.27 to Alberto Camero, who\nwas suspended as constable by\nGovernor Dave Sholtz in 1935.\nIt has been decided to pull\ndown the Lancaster house ojv\nWhiteKead street, near Southard;\nwhich was built more than 100\nyears ago. A part of the house\ncollapsed a week ago during a\nheavy rainstorm.\nMrs. Anthony Perez left this\nmorning for Tampa to visit rela\ntives. Ilf/' i\nj; i\nMrs. Annie Page and daughter,\nMarguerite, who have beeri visit\ning in Miami., returned today.\nMr. and Mis. Joseph Beaver\nleft yesterday for Cincinnati to\nbe present at the exercises when\ntheir daughter, Mary, graduates\nfrom the University of Cincin\nnati. f\nMiss Louise Hawkes won the\nprize for the highest score and\nMrs. Arthur Sheppard, Jr., was\nawarded the consolation prize at\na card party* given yesterday by\nthe Junior Woman's Club.\nToday The Citizen says in an\neditorial paragraph:\n\u201cBill collectors report they are\nmeeting with a most cordial atti\ntude in making their rounds and\nhave been asked repeatedly to\ncall again.\u201d\nFAITH VINDICATED\nBERKLEY, Calif. Janet\nCasey, 5, put her tooth under her\npillow, confident that the good\nfairies would put a penny under\nthe pillow during the night.\nWhen she awakened, however,\nthere was no penny. X-rays at a\nhospital vindicated her faith,\nhowever. The penny was inside\nbrother Michael, 4, who had\nawakened first.\nOnly ten per cent of U. S.\nforeign commerce was carried in\nAmerican ships at the close of\nthe 19th Century.\nPolitical\nAnnouncement\nFor City Commission\nALBERT G. ROBERTS\nYour Oroesr SELLS That Good\nSTAR \u2605BRAND\nAmerican rArrfr\nand CUBAN tiUff f KjEj\nTRY A POUND TODAY\nTODAY\u2019S\nANNIVERSARIES\n-i* r\n(Know America)\n1844\u2014Herbert L. Bridgman.\nBrooklyn. N. Y. newspaper pub\nUsher, patron of Peary\u2019s Arctic\nexplorations, born m Amherst,\nMass. Died Sept. 24, 1924.\n1850\u2014William Lawrence, em\ninent Boston Protestant Episco\npal bishop, born in Boston. Died\nNov. 6, 1941.\n1874\u2014Josephine Preston Pea\nbody, poetic dramatist and lyric\npoet, born in New York. Died\nDec. 4, 1922.\n1886\u2014Randolph Bourne, bril\nliant essayist and thinker, un\ntimely cut off, born in Bloom\nfield, N. J. Died in influenza\nepidemic, Dec. 22, 1918.\n1892\u2014Raymond Clapper, fam\nous cohimnistrcommentator, born\nin Linn Cos., Kansas. Killed in\nplane crash, over the Marshall\nIslands, Feb. 2, 1944.\nLEGALS\nIV THK CIRCUIT (OI HT THK\nKLKVKVTH 41 1111 IAI, CIRCUIT\nOK THK HTATK OK KI.OKIDA.\nIN A Nil KOR MONROK COl NTV,\nIN CHANCKHY.\n\u2022M> N*. 11-840\nWILLIAM L. II.UtK.SKKS,\nPlaintiff,\nvn 111 VABK'F\n-MARY ACUKRA M< N 1 XTV HAItKr\nNKSS. Ti- V* 4\nDefenilatit.\nOHDRR OF PUBLICATION\nTO: Mary Agrus McNulty liafk\n\n116 South Ash Street,\nMindert, Louisiana.\nYou are hereby required to ap- n\nnear to the 14111 of Complaint for\nPivoro* in the above styled cause\non or before the !4th day of June,\nA. I>. ISIS, otherwise the allegations\ntherein wilt he taken as confessed,\n.This Order is to he published once\nweek for four consecutive weeks\nin The Key West Citizen, a news\npaper published uttKey West, Mon\nroe County, Florida.\nItoiie and Ordered this 7th day of\nMay, A. I. 1949.\n<Ken| KARL R. ADAMS,\nClerk of the Circuit Court,\nMonroe County, Flor Ma.\nBy: <sd> Anrse C. Lhngworth,\nDeputy Clerk\n.1. Y. Porter IV,\nSolicitor for Plaintiff.\nmay-9-IG-23-30,1949.\nIN 'OHH CIRCUIT COURT OK THK\nKI.KVKNTM JUDICIAL CIRCUIT\nOK TDK MTATK OK FLORIDA,\nIN AND FOR MONROK COUNTY,-\nIN UHANUKRY.\nrase No. 11 -WO\nIIA HOLLO DCP.AN BONNE,\nPlaintiff,\nVS. RIVORCK\nMARIA CRUZ I\u2019.ONNK,\nDefendant.\nOllDF.n OF PUBLICATION'\nTO: Maria Crux Bonne,\n5 West 116th Street,\nNew York, N. Y.\nYou are hereby required to ap\npear to the Bill of Complaint for\nDivorce in the above styled cause\n-in or before the 13th day of June,\nA. I). 1040, otherwise the allegations\ntherein will be taken as confessed.\nThis Order is to he published once\na week for four consecutive weeks\nin The Key *\\Yk>rt Citizen, a news\npaper published at Key West, Mon\nroe County, Florida.\nDone and Ordered this 7th day of\nMay, A. D. 1949.\n(Seal KARL R. ADAMS,\no'erk of the Circuit Court,\nMonroe County, Florida.\nBy: <sd) Anne C. Longworth,\nDeptily Clerk\n.1. Y. Porter IV,\nSolicitor for Plaintiff.\nniay-9-IG-23-30.1949.\nnniM\ntX V whmltmgm Wfe ESS\n)mn wn an n,wt ims ms im>\nOM4 04 MS MSS St Mis V\ntan mm iia t jamb tarns\nMS MPft 15,499 I9,*M JW\nyour:/**\"*'\n01 NO OTHER ONEinH\nBy Helen It Woodward j\nChapter 12\nr%AN HOLLOWAY came into\nI the kitchen where his mother\nand younger brother, Mike, still\nlingered at the supper table. He\nwore new dark blue suit with a\nneat pin-stripe, a dark blue tie,\nand I.e smelled of good soap and\nshaving lotion. He had a coat over\nhis arm, his hat in his hand. His\nblack hair shone from much\ni brushing and his blue eyes were\n1 saining, fie looked like thousands\nof other youhg men who were\nmost likely at this same momeht\nsetting forth to spend the etfe\nning with their best girls.\nMike cried, \"Hey, Dan\u2014you\nsaid you\u2019d help with my algebra!\nDan showed his white teeth Jn\na grin. \u201cSure, l will. But not tb-\nnight Other things on my mihd\ntonigftt\u201d\n\u201cWhat kinda things?\"\n\u201cWhere are you going, Dan?\"\nHe laughed. \u201cSince when have\nI had to face an inquisition before\ngoing put?\u201d\n\u201cBut you look so sort of spe\ni cial!\u201d\n\u201cI\u2019m going to see Martina Way\nland!\u201d\n\u2018Who\u2019s Martina Waylaiui?\u201d\nMike wanted to know, his scom\nful freckled face wrinkled into a\nscowl of disappointment\nHattie Holloway\u2019s face, too,\nclouded and she felt her heart\ni 5 catch on a sharp corner of fear.\n\u201cOh! Dan! Why?\u201d\n\u201cWhy?\" he shouted in amaze\nment \u201cNow., look. Mom\u2014why\ndoes my. guy-*?\u201d\n\u201c1 knew. Bat Martina Way\niandl\u201d\n\u201cWhat\u2019s wrong with her?\u201d\n\u201cNothing, of course. Only don\u2019t\nyou think she simply lives in a\ndifferent world?\"\nHis brows met over his straight\nnose. \u201cI hadn\u2019t noticed it!\u201d\n\u201cHer life is entirely different\nfrom yours.\"\n\u201cSo what? I think she\u2019s\u2014she\u2019s\nHe could find no words to\nsay what he really thought. He\nfinished in his own mind\u2014\u201cter\nribly sweet!\u201d But he knew Mike\nwould have howled, and his\nmother wouldn\u2019t have understood\nif he\u2019d said them aloud. Suddenly\nhe was on the defensive, and he\ndidn\u2019t like it He asked, almost\nangrily, \u201cYou mean you don\u2019t\nIt is believed that platinum\nwas brought to Europe for the\nfirst time in 1941 from Cartagena,\nColumbia, by a Jamaican assay\ner.\nLEGALS\nIN TDK CIRCUIT COURT OF THK\nKLKVKNTIt JUDICIAL CIRCUIT,\nOK THK MTATK OK FLORIDA, t\nIN AND FOR MONROK COUNTY.\nIN ((lANCKRY.\nCr No. 11-N72\nJOHN A. SILVA, JR.\nPlaintiff,\nvs. DINOKCK\nFRANCKS O. SILVA,\nDefendant.\nOHDKH OK PI HLIt ATIOV\nTO: Frances O. Silva,\n105 Rogers Ave., Apt.\nNuffylk 6. Virginia.\nYou ere hereby required to ap\npear to the Bill of Complaint for\nI ivorce in the above styled cause\non or before the 30th day of June, 1\nA. D. 1040, otherwise the allegations\ntherein will be taken as confessed, i\nThis order is to be published once\na week for f<>ur -consecutive weeks\nin The Key West Citizen, a news- j\npaper published in Key West, .Mon- j\nroe County, Florida.\nDone and ordered this 20th day j\nof May, A. I). 1040.\n<Seal> KARL R. ADAMS.\nClerk of the Circuit Court, j\n.Monroe County, Florida.\nBy: (sd) Florence K. Sawyer, j\nDeputy Clerk.\nJ. V. Porter IV,\nSolicitor for Plaintiff.\nmay-30; june-6-13-20,1949. j\nIN THK CIRCUIT COl IIT OK THK\nKI.KYKNTH JUDICIAL CIRCUIT!\nOK THK STATK OK FLORIDA,\nIN AND FOH MONROK COl NTV.\nIN CHANCKHY. 1\nCase No. 11 -HOT\nRI\u2019TH K. McANDRKWS,\nPlaintiff.\nvs. DIYOHCK\nJ. D. McANDRKWS,\nDefendant.\nORDP.n OK PI BLICATION\nAND NOTICK TO APPKAH\nTO: J. I. McANDRKWS,\n420 Peach Street,\nKrie, Pennsylvania.\nYou 4are hereby required to ap\npear to the sworn bill of Cdmplaint J\nfiled against you in the above en- j\ntitled cause, on or before the 27th j\nday of June, A. D. 1040: otherwise\nthe allegations of this bill will be j\ntaken as confessed by you.\nDONIO AND ORDKRKD at Key;\nWest, Florida, this 21st day of May,\nA. I 1049. i\nKARL R. ADAMS, I\nClerk of the Circuit Court,\nMonroe County, Florida.\nBy: (sd) Anne C. Longworth, i\nDeputy Clerk.\nCt. Ct. Seal.\nTt.M O, WATKINS,\nAttorney for Plaintiff.\nmay-271-30; june-O-13,1949 i\nthink she\u2019s good enough for me,\nor me for her?\u201d\nHattie knew she had bean\nwrong to even say as much as she\nhad. She smiled and came around\nthe table to look up at her tall\nson. \u201cYou know I think you\u2019re\ngood enough for anyone on earth,\nand I\u2019m sure Miss Way land is a\nmost worthy girl! I\u2014l just didn\u2019t\nknow you were interested in\nher!\u201d\n\u201cWell, I am!\" he answered, still\nbelligerent\nHattie managed a pretty au\nthentic laugh. \u201cAll right So you\nare. Have j good time, Dan.\"\nHe kissed her cheek. \u201cThat\u2019s\nbetter. So long. I\u2019ve got to rush.\nShe lives twenty-five miles in the\ncountry!\u201d\nHe banged the door loudly be\nhind him. \u201cJeepers! He needn\u2019t\nshake the house down!\u201d Mike ob\nserved. His eyes went to the small\nradio on the kitchen cabinet\n\u201cGuess I\u2019ll just listen to the\nFBl\u2014*\n\u201cI guess you won\u2019t l Hattie said\nfirmly. \u201cYou\u2019ve forgotten I went\nto school and studied algebra, too.\nBesides maybe Nora will coma.\"\n\u201cAw, Mom\u2014\" Mike began, but\nfrom the look on her face he\nknew there would be no argu\nment about it He would get nia\nalgebra. _\n\u201cI\u2019ll efear the table and you\ncan work there while I do the\ndishes. If you hurry you can be\nfinished by eight and then we\u2019ll\nlisten to one of the later mys\nteries.\u201d\nThe kitchen grew quiet except\nfor the rattle of the dishes\u2014quiet\nenough for Hattie Holloway to\ncollect her thoughts. They were\nnot exactly unmixed with appre\nhension She had always felt to\nsure than Dan and Nora\u2014\nTHE highway stretched before\nDan like a clean white ribbon\nin the moonlight It was com\npletely cleared now of its former\ncovering of treacherous sleet The\nair was beginning to have a touch\nof the promise of spring. He low\nered the window and let it sweep\ninto the car, fresh and invigorat\ning as new wine.\nHis thoughts raced ahead of the\nspeeding car. Does she feel it too\n\u2014he wondered\u2014this high lilting\nexcitement that was like nothing\nhe had ever k town? Had she\nbeen conscious, as he had, of the\nTODAY\u2019S BIRTHDAYS\n(Know America)\nCornelia Otis Skinner, mono\nloguist, born in Chicago, 49 years\nago.\nWilliam Phillips of New York,\nonetime undersecretary of state,\nborn in Beverly, Mass., 71 years\nago.\nMrs. Harper Sibley of Roches\nter, N. Y.. president of the Unit\ned Council of Church Women,\nborn in Orange, N. J., 62 years\nago.\nBenny Goodman, band leader, j\nborn in Chicago, 40 years ago. I\nFormer Postmaster James A.\nFarley of New York, chairman\nof the Coco Cola Export Corp.,\nborn Greely Point, N. Y. 61 years\nago.\nEx-Postmaster General Frank\nC. Walker, born in Plymouth, Pa.,\n63 years ago.\nRosa Raisa, soprano, born in\nPoland, 56 years ago.\nGeorge A. Sloan of New York,\ncivic worker, born in Nashville.\nTenn., 56 years ago.\nSTRONG ABM BRAND COITD\nTRIUMPH tjL\nCOFFEE V iSrv\nMHX\nAll Grocer\nOverseas Transportation\nCompany, Inc.\nFast, Dependable Freight and Fxproaa Survtoa\nMIAMI andMKEY VEST\nAlso AU. jynrrQ FLOEXDA KEYS\nExpress Schedulet\n(Mo Hops En Mil\nLEAVES KKYWEST DAO.Y (EX\nCEPT SUNDAYS) at MB PJI. Ar\nrives at Miami at UiM o\u2019claak MM\nnight.\nLEAVES MIAMI DAILY (EXCOT\nSUNDAYS) at I